{"questionId":"19839","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>It is believed that the power <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> of a signal at a point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math> km from an antenna is inversely proportional to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>d</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></math> where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math> is recorded at distances of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>&nbsp;to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>&nbsp;and the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>P</mi></math> are plotted on the graph below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/1a6dcd959befb58f4af3b2e4390140e7c2967109.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>P</mi></math> are shown in the table below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/1a12d8a215fe1b44c5c0b4064d459abd96169581.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the equation of the least squares regression line of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>P</mi></math>&nbsp;against <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>040</mn><mo>…</mo><mo> </mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12632</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≈</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo> </mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>d</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>126</mn></math> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>A1A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note: A1</strong> for each correct term.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19839","referenceCode":"EXN.1.AHL.TZ0.12b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the equation of the least squares regression line of log10 P against log10 d.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, scatter diagrams, eqn of y on x","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.10—Scaling large numbers, log-log graphs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}